## Summary

Implement data salvage feature that enables zero data loss after force failover by capturing and exposing the salvage checkpoint, along with a DumpMessages API to retrieve unsynchronized messages.

## Motivation

When a force failover occurs (promoting a secondary cluster to primary when the original primary is unavailable), there may be messages that were written to the old primary but not yet replicated to the secondary. Currently, these messages are lost after force failover.

The data salvage feature allows users to:
1. Identify the last synced position (salvage checkpoint) captured during force promote
2. Retrieve unsynchronized messages from the old primary cluster using the DumpMessages API
3. Replay these messages to achieve zero data loss

## Design

### SalvageCheckpoint
- Captured in-memory when `force_promote=true` is set during `UpdateReplicateConfiguration`
- Contains the last synced position from the old primary (message_id, timetick, pchannel, cluster_id)
- Persisted to a separate etcd key for durability
- Exposed via `GetReplicateInfo` response

### DumpMessages API
- Streaming RPC that reads messages from WAL starting from a given position
- Supports timetick-based filtering (start_timetick, end_timetick)
- Filters out system messages (TimeTick, CreateSegment, Flush, RollbackTxn)
- Returns only replicable messages useful for data recovery

## API Changes

### GetReplicateInfoResponse
```protobuf
message GetReplicateInfoResponse {
    common.Status status = 1;
    common.ReplicateCheckpoint checkpoint = 2;
    common.ReplicateCheckpoint salvage_checkpoint = 3;  // NEW
}
```

### DumpMessages RPC
```protobuf
rpc DumpMessages(DumpMessagesRequest) returns (stream DumpMessagesResponse){}

message DumpMessagesRequest {
  string pchannel = 1;
  common.MessageID start_message_id = 2;
  uint64 start_timetick = 3;
  uint64 end_timetick = 4;
  bool start_position_exclusive = 5;
}

message DumpMessagesResponse {
  oneof response {
    common.Status status = 1;
    common.ImmutableMessage message = 2;
  }
}
```

## Usage Flow

1. After force failover on cluster B, call `GetReplicateInfo` to get the `salvage_checkpoint`
2. Connect to the old primary (cluster A) and call `DumpMessages` with the salvage checkpoint
3. Replay the returned messages to cluster B to recover lost data
